1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:26,292
Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambuddhassa

2
00:00:26,896 --> 00:00:34,744
Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed, Noble and Fully Self-Enlightened One.

3
00:00:34,765 --> 00:00:47,320
So, I want to just make one more talk devoted to Dependent Regeneration and it's really looking at another model.

4
00:00:50,543 --> 00:00:56,851
So, if I go through the model, then you'll see that it offers a slightly different perspective.

5
00:00:59,497 --> 00:01:02,982
So remember that we begin with this avijja, ignorance, right?

6
00:01:03,042 --> 00:01:10,253
So we start from the platform of not knowing, but this not knowing produces a certain delusion.

7
00:01:10,653 --> 00:01:13,858
So a delusion is the wrong way of looking at something.

8
00:01:14,578 --> 00:01:19,885
And because of that, we've created in the past these sankharas.

9
00:01:19,906 --> 00:01:22,890
So sankharas are basically all our habits.

10
00:01:23,292 --> 00:01:24,373
We'll put it just down to that.

11
00:01:24,713 --> 00:01:28,319
But the important thing is that they've been produced by an act of will.

12
00:01:29,760 --> 00:01:32,484
In other words, we produce them.

13
00:01:32,504 --> 00:01:37,951
We don't particularly produce what we see, it's just natural to the body, it's natural to the sense base.

14
00:01:38,352 --> 00:01:41,537
But what you do with what you see is within your power.

15
00:01:43,980 --> 00:01:54,227
And these two things, the fundamental not knowing, the delusion and the habits are running concurrent beneath every moment.

16
00:01:54,578 --> 00:02:17,969
and then within every moment you've got to have this basic trilogy so the first one is the potential of cognition which is the primary act of knowing and this doesn't happen unless you've got a body and mind so the two lean against each other

17
00:02:18,557 --> 00:02:46,556
and because there's a body and mind you've got your six sense bases so there's your basic human being and it's through that that you make contact with the world so that's your first active moment right contact and there has to be an object there has to be a sense base and there has to be that act of cognition from there you've got your from that you've got your basic sensations and then we

18
00:02:47,026 --> 00:03:15,497
Divide the world into what we like what we don't like and there's an area of neutrality But if you look at that more closely it always shades off into liking not liking And that's the we might call the basic duality of the world, but that's not suffering now this it's at the next point that these sankaras these Volitional conditionings begin to rise in the form of desires and that's your tanha remember that

19
00:03:15,882 --> 00:03:20,027
There's another word in Pali, chanda, which means a good desire, such as desire to meditate.

20
00:03:20,147 --> 00:03:25,596
But tanha is a word specific to those desires which arise out of delusion.

21
00:03:26,937 --> 00:03:32,907
And out of that, the next moment is that moment of identity, self.

22
00:03:33,568 --> 00:03:37,153
And that's the point actually where you start suffering.

23
00:03:37,174 --> 00:03:41,400
The point where you identify with what it is you want.

24
00:03:42,122 --> 00:04:00,199
and as soon as you've done that it's almost impossible to stop the energy going into that process which is going to make it come out of a potential of a desire into an actual some form of action and that's your becoming, that's your karma and then as soon as you act

25
00:04:00,584 --> 00:04:05,651
There has to be a beginning of the action, the middle section, and the end of it.

26
00:04:05,752 --> 00:04:07,715
So that's your birth, aging and death.

27
00:04:08,455 --> 00:04:15,686
Now, that's your fundamental dependent origination rolling on every so often.

28
00:04:16,047 --> 00:04:17,269
Not all the time, remember.

29
00:04:17,649 --> 00:04:20,533
It's only when, really, it's activated through this desire.

30
00:04:21,033 --> 00:04:22,836
So it obviously doesn't happen when you're asleep.

31
00:04:23,478 --> 00:04:25,461
It doesn't happen in neutral actions either.

32
00:04:26,538 --> 00:04:30,002
But that doesn't mean to say that the fundamental delusion isn't there.

33
00:04:30,202 --> 00:04:34,889
That's running constantly underneath every moment of our lives.

34
00:04:34,908 --> 00:04:40,456
Now, in the diagram here, you see, all this produces suffering.

35
00:04:41,076 --> 00:04:44,040
And the Buddha says, dukkha, that's the dukkha, yeah?

36
00:04:44,060 --> 00:04:47,865
And the Buddha says that it's because of suffering that we seek the end of suffering.

37
00:04:47,886 --> 00:04:49,827
That might be pretty obvious, but...

38
00:04:50,584 --> 00:04:53,870
It's because we don't want to suffer that we begin to seek the end of suffering.

39
00:04:53,930 --> 00:04:57,033
So suffering itself is the cause for the end of suffering.

40
00:04:59,057 --> 00:05:03,403
And the way this comes about is through three things.

41
00:05:03,963 --> 00:05:06,047
First of all, this wise reflection.

42
00:05:07,870 --> 00:05:19,966
The Buddha is very keen on this yoni-so-maneshi-kāra so that every so often you actually look back upon your actions and work out what we've done which is harmful to ourselves.

43
00:05:20,369 --> 00:05:25,557
In a sense, that's the action of conscience.

44
00:05:25,576 --> 00:05:29,923
Interestingly enough, there's no word in Pali for our word conscience.

45
00:05:30,524 --> 00:05:32,045
But that's another talk.

46
00:05:32,065 --> 00:05:41,680
And this wise reflection, remember, brings about a certain confidence.

47
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:44,925
And that's what we mean by this faith, this confidence.

48
00:05:45,343 --> 00:05:49,733
And it's through the confidence that we begin to act in skillful ways.

49
00:05:50,555 --> 00:06:01,338
And as soon as we do that, it takes away all the guilt, all the shame, all the remorse from our lives and there's a natural gladness arises.

50
00:06:02,322 --> 00:06:04,786
So there's a natural peacefulness in the mind.

51
00:06:06,555 --> 00:06:11,100
And with this peacefulness there comes a deeper peacefulness of a rapture.

52
00:06:11,721 --> 00:06:20,668
It has also a certain calmness to it, and you'll see that some of these qualities are part of the seven factors of enlightenment.

53
00:06:21,250 --> 00:06:24,492
And this produces a certain contentment, a certain happiness.

54
00:06:25,514 --> 00:06:33,521
Now, it's when you've got that sort of emotional base within the mind that, of course, concentration arises naturally.

55
00:06:33,802 --> 00:06:34,942
It's easy.

56
00:06:35,377 --> 00:06:58,887
and remember what empowers this is the desire to want to know and even when something horrible is happening within us even when we've got a depression as soon as you turn towards an investigation towards that mode that interest immediately you can feel that

57
00:06:59,932 --> 00:07:04,622
at another level or a part of it or beneath it, there is this very subtle joy.

58
00:07:04,641 --> 00:07:13,620
And that joy is actually mirroring the liberation, the detachment from the mental state that we're experiencing.

59
00:07:14,156 --> 00:07:22,209
So, with that concentration and with that investigation there arises the knowledge and the insight, the one moves into the other.

60
00:07:22,670 --> 00:07:31,663
And this knowledge and insight, remember, is always into these three characteristics, anicca, dukkha and atma, because these are manifestations of our delusion.

61
00:07:33,326 --> 00:07:42,560
And with those little insights, and let's say that there are classic insights which lead to these paths and fruits.

62
00:07:43,992 --> 00:07:47,778
And as it were, they're cut-off points because you can't fall down from that.

63
00:07:48,338 --> 00:07:52,766
It's like when we reach the age of six, seven, and Father Christmas can't exist anymore.

64
00:07:53,107 --> 00:07:54,930
You can't go back to believing it.

65
00:07:55,250 --> 00:07:55,992
It's not possible.

66
00:07:56,273 --> 00:07:57,113
You've got to kid yourself.

67
00:07:59,036 --> 00:08:05,528
You can't go back to that open belief that Father Christmas is going to appear from Lapland with Rudolph.

68
00:08:06,014 --> 00:08:13,684
So what happens is, just like with Father Christmas, you become disenchanted with that.

69
00:08:13,723 --> 00:08:15,165
You don't believe in it anymore.

70
00:08:15,627 --> 00:08:16,949
And that's your disenchantment.

71
00:08:17,249 --> 00:08:25,059
And that's a really beautiful word for it because we tend to be enchanted by the world, bewitched by the world.

72
00:08:25,800 --> 00:08:31,447
And it's this knowledge, this understanding which undermines that bewitchment, that enchantment.

73
00:08:32,052 --> 00:08:40,004
Now, these moments of bewitchment and enchantment don't have to be huge, fantastic insights.

74
00:08:41,347 --> 00:08:47,258
They're just little understandings that keep coming to us all the time.

75
00:08:47,818 --> 00:08:54,389
And what's happening is there's a slow movement in consciousness, a slow movement in the way we're seeing the world.

76
00:08:55,110 --> 00:08:57,434
And this begins to accumulate, this begins to grow.

77
00:08:57,922 --> 00:09:04,288
And it manifests in the way we feel about things, the way we respond to things rather than react.

78
00:09:04,989 --> 00:09:09,033
It manifests in the heart as compassion, love, sympathetic joy.

79
00:09:09,072 --> 00:09:25,009
These are all qualities that arise because we're undermining that fundamental delusion which is causing this root selfishness where we can only see the world from the way that we see it and for our own benefit.

80
00:09:26,575 --> 00:09:32,265
And as soon as that disenchantment comes, all the emotions around bewitchment disappear.

81
00:09:32,566 --> 00:09:34,009
And that's your dispassion.

82
00:09:34,629 --> 00:09:38,356
That's where the heart's beginning to really cleanse itself.

83
00:09:38,376 --> 00:09:42,745
And it's at these little moments that we experience these liberations.

84
00:09:43,078 --> 00:09:55,902
And that liberation is the quality of freedom that the Buddha talks about, which is the essential feel of Nibbāna.

85
00:09:56,423 --> 00:09:58,486
So we get little insights like that, you see.

86
00:09:59,427 --> 00:10:01,251
Nibbāna itself is a technical word.

87
00:10:01,292 --> 00:10:03,635
It refers to the final end.

88
00:10:03,903 --> 00:10:32,931
it's phrased as parson fruits and nibbana but that doesn't mean to say that we can't get a little inkling as to what it is to be liberated from these desires and all that takes us to what's known as the destruction of the outflows the asawa which will be my talk next week my little ten minute effort next week so

89
00:10:33,568 --> 00:11:00,167
you've got this wheel of dependent origination it's constantly turning and then slowly there's an awakening of hey I'm suffering so as soon as that recognition of hey I'm suffering comes up then there's the desire to escape it and it's through this reflection it's through faith it's through good action that the faith begins to arise that in fact the path that we're on is actually leading out of it

90
00:11:00,772 --> 00:11:17,278
this leads to a natural gladness which leads to a deeper state of rapture which is that interest which is wanting to know how to get out of this but that must be matched with calmness remember with calmness

91
00:11:17,258 --> 00:11:36,076
and then there comes this sort of general happiness with things and it's within that atmosphere that the concentration easily grows and with it this investigation and it's in the investigation that these knowledges and insights arise

92
00:11:36,529 --> 00:11:39,695
And as soon as we see something, we become disenchanted.

93
00:11:40,275 --> 00:11:49,892
For instance, it's like when you overeat, and then afterwards you feel bloated, you feel heavy with it, and you have a little reflection.

94
00:11:50,111 --> 00:11:52,797
You say, well, this is caused by overeating.

95
00:11:53,258 --> 00:11:56,842
So the next time I see food, I'll go a bit more gently on it.

96
00:11:57,423 --> 00:12:00,850
There's all these little gross examples, but as you become disenchanted,

97
00:12:00,998 --> 00:12:27,748
more and more subtle within the way you observe your own psychology you see every time there's an indulgence there's always an aftermath of dissatisfaction and it's really beginning to feel the dissatisfaction which leads you to the end of it so long as when the dissatisfaction comes up you keep going back to another pleasurable state to as it were hide it from ourselves then we're not actually seeing the suffering

98
00:12:28,066 --> 00:12:55,744
and so unwittingly we keep pounding this, we keep pounding the beat round and round, it's dependent origination and it's really catching the aftermath, the effects of indulgence which makes us want to stop indulging so that's part of your knowledge and insight that brings about the disenchantment with the world as a place we can seek happiness, that's all it's saying

99
00:12:56,163 --> 00:12:59,607
Which, remember, is not a denial of the pleasures and joys of life.

100
00:13:00,089 --> 00:13:04,796
It's that wrong relationship of thinking that this is true happiness.

101
00:13:06,258 --> 00:13:15,052
And that's what leads us to this lovely place where, you know, we're enjoying things, but there's that dispassion, right?

102
00:13:15,072 --> 00:13:22,001
And remember, the English word passion is quite lovely because it comes from the Latin to mean, I suffer, right?

103
00:13:23,500 --> 00:13:24,542
And that's the liberation.

104
00:13:24,822 --> 00:13:26,764
That's the feeling of liberation.

105
00:13:26,784 --> 00:13:33,173
And slowly through this, we're undermining these āsa words, which I'll talk about next week, these outflows.

106
00:13:33,975 --> 00:13:43,710
And that's looking at depend origination as a joyful process, or at least the process out of which we can find our liberation.

107
00:13:45,192 --> 00:13:52,241
So I can only hope that my words have been of some assistance and that you will struggle against the old habits

108
00:13:53,234 --> 00:13:59,937
and release yourself from the pain of suffering sooner rather than later.

